<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-26T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-26T23:00:00-05:00" n="37" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d37">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/1297:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-27T12:00:00+08:00">February 27,
                                1934—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received February 27—2:22 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>101. The following telegram has been received from the Consul General at
                            Harbin.</p>
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“February 26, 4 p.m. Engineer Kalina and other five railway prisoners
                                released on February 24th, and expected soon to go to Russia. Their
                                places on railway has been taken by other Soviet Russians. Presumed
                                that Tokyo conference will be resumed and that Soviet Russia will
                                sell railway thereby commencing end of Russian influence in North
                                Manchuria.[”]</p>
                        </quote>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>